(SMART CAMPUS API CONCEPTUAL REPORT) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(1.1 JAX-RS Resource Lifecycle And Thread Safety) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The default JAX-RS resource lifecycle is request scoped. The runtime normally creates a new) Tj
T*
(resource class instance for each incoming HTTP request. That means instance fields inside) Tj
T*
(resource classes should not be treated as long-lived shared storage, because a different) Tj
T*
(resource instance may handle the next request.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(For this coursework, shared state is placed in a singleton CampusStore, not in resource) Tj
T*
(instance fields. The store uses ConcurrentHashMap for the main collections and synchronized) Tj
T*
(methods for compound operations that must be atomic, such as registering a sensor and adding) Tj
T*
(its ID to the parent room, deleting a room only after checking its sensors, and adding a) Tj
T*
(reading while updating the parent sensor's currentValue. This avoids lost updates and race) Tj
T*
(conditions while still keeping the implementation in memory as required.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(1.2 Discovery Endpoint And HATEOAS) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Hypermedia is a hallmark of advanced RESTful design because responses do not only return) Tj
T*
(data; they also show clients where related actions and resources are located. The discovery) Tj
T*
(endpoint returns version information, contact details, and links to the main collections.) Tj
T*
(This makes the API more self-documenting and helps client developers navigate from the API) Tj
T*
(root to rooms, sensors, and readings without hard-coding every URL from separate) Tj
T*
(documentation.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Static documentation can become stale when routes change. Hypermedia links travel with the) Tj
T*
(API response, so clients can discover supported navigation paths at runtime and reduce) Tj
T*
(coupling to fixed URL assumptions.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2.1 Returning Room IDs Versus Full Room Objects) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Returning only room IDs keeps payloads smaller and saves bandwidth, especially when there) Tj
T*
(are thousands of rooms or mobile clients with limited network capacity. However, clients) Tj
T*
(then need to make extra requests to fetch each room's name, capacity, and sensor list, which) Tj
T*
(increases latency and client-side processing.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Returning full room objects costs more bandwidth but gives clients immediately useful data) Tj
T*
(in one response. For this coursework, GET /rooms returns full room objects because) Tj
T*
(facilities managers need a comprehensive overview and the rubric asks for a comprehensive) Tj
T*
(room list.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2.2 DELETE Idempotency) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The successful room deletion operation is idempotent in server-state terms. If a client) Tj
T*
(deletes an empty room such as HALL-100, the first request removes it and returns 204 No) Tj
T*
(Content. If the same request is sent again, the room is still absent, and the server state) Tj
T*
(remains unchanged. The response can still be 204 No Content because the desired state, "this) Tj
T*
(room no longer exists", has already been achieved.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(For a room with assigned sensors, repeated DELETE requests return 409 Conflict and leave the) Tj
T*
(room unchanged each time. That also keeps the server state stable across repeated identical) Tj
T*
(requests.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3.1 @Consumes And Media Type Mismatches) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The @Consumes\(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON\) annotation tells JAX-RS that the method accepts) Tj
T*
(JSON request bodies. If a client sends text/plain or application/xml to that method, Jersey) Tj
T*
ET
endstream
