(cannot match the request entity media type to the resource method. The runtime rejects the) Tj
T*
(request before the method logic executes and returns 415 Unsupported Media Type.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This protects the API from trying to deserialize unsupported formats as Java POJOs. In this) Tj
T*
(project, the WebApplicationExceptionMapper converts that failure into a structured JSON) Tj
T*
(error response instead of a default server page.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3.2 Query Parameters Versus Path Parameters For Filtering) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Path parameters are best for identifying a specific resource or nested resource, such as) Tj
T*
(/sensors/CO2-001. Query parameters are better for filtering, searching, sorting, and) Tj
T*
(optional modifiers on a collection, such as /sensors?type=CO2.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The query parameter approach is superior here because type is not a unique resource) Tj
T*
(identity. It is a search criterion that may match many sensors or no sensors. Query) Tj
T*
(parameters also scale naturally if more filters are added later, such as status=ACTIVE or) Tj
T*
(roomId=LIB-301, without creating awkward nested paths for every possible search combination.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4.1 Sub-Resource Locator Benefits) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The sub-resource locator in SensorResource delegates /sensors/{sensorId}/readings to a) Tj
T*
(dedicated SensorReadingResource. This keeps the main sensor controller focused on sensor) Tj
T*
(collection and sensor detail operations, while reading history logic is isolated in a class) Tj
T*
(that understands the selected parent sensor context.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(In larger APIs, this pattern prevents one massive controller from containing every nested) Tj
T*
(path such as sensors, readings, reading IDs, and future reading analytics. It improves) Tj
T*
(maintainability, testing, readability, and separation of responsibilities.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5.2 Why 422 Is Better Than 404 For Missing Payload References) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(When a client posts a sensor with a non-existent roomId, the endpoint /sensors exists and) Tj
T*
(the JSON body may be syntactically valid. The problem is semantic: the payload references a) Tj
T*
(room that cannot be linked. 422 Unprocessable Entity describes that situation more) Tj
T*
(accurately than 404 Not Found.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A 404 would suggest the requested URL was missing. Here the URL is valid, but the server) Tj
T*
(cannot process the entity because one of its internal references violates business rules.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5.4 Cybersecurity Risks Of Stack Traces) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Raw Java stack traces expose implementation details that attackers can use. They may reveal) Tj
T*
(package names, class names, method names, line numbers, server file paths, framework) Tj
T*
(versions, dependency names, and internal control flow. That information helps attackers) Tj
T*
(fingerprint the technology stack and search for known vulnerabilities or weak points.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The global exception mapper returns a generic 500 Internal Server Error JSON body to) Tj
T*
(external clients while logging the real exception internally for developers. This keeps the) Tj
T*
(API leak-proof without losing observability.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5.5 Why Filters Are Better For Logging) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Logging is a cross-cutting concern because it applies to every endpoint rather than one) Tj
T*
(business operation. A JAX-RS request/response filter centralizes that concern in one class,) Tj
T*
(so every incoming request and outgoing status code is logged consistently.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(If Logger.info\(\) calls were manually placed in every resource method, the code would become) Tj
T*
